                                WildCards.

        Wildcards are an incredibly useful way of saving you fingers from
wearing out. These can be used wherever a normal filename would occur, but
can speed up a lot of operations.

        There are two symbols that AmigaDOS uses: the '#' hash symbol
(known as the 'pound' symbol by Americans) and the '?' question mark. If
you are used to the PC and MS-DOS then you'll have some re-learning to do,
as the '*' star isn't used by default.

        When used in a filename, a '?' means 'any character' so the list of
following filenames are all equivalent:

                               testfile1.dat
                               testfile?.dat
                               test???1/dat
                              ?testfile1.da?
                               ?????????.???

        The 'hash' mark is used to mean 'any number of (or no) characters',
so the following filenames are all equal:

                                aafile.xxx
                                #afile.xxx
                                 #afile.#x
                               #p#aafile.#x

        Now the combination of the wildcard symbols is what makes them most
useful. The following files are all equal. Remember that AmigaDOS is very
flexible with filenames, and certainly doesn't limit them to a group of
eight characters, a full stop and three more characters.

                              my_picture.iff
                               my_picture.#?
                                 my_#?.iff
                                   my#?
                                    #?

        Now for some practical examples. Say you had a list of images which
you needed to copy from one disk to another. All the pictures had different
names, but you had the foresight to include 'iff' somewhere in their names.
For example, they might be like this: John.iff, BindyTheCatIFF, IFF_of_Sam.

        You can copy all these files with one command: copy df0:#?iff#? to
df1: The wildcards will get anything which has 'iff' somewhere in it. Note
that AmigaDOS is not case specific. If the files are all stored in a
directory called 'pictures' you would use a CLI command like this:

Copy df0:pictures/#?iff#? to df1:

        If you wanted to re-create the directory, include the name of the
new directory. like this:

copy df0:pictures/#?iff#? to df1:pictures

        This will create a new directory, and copy only the files with
'iff' in their names into it. If you don't want to see a list of filenames,
but QUIET at the end of the command, like this:

copy df0:pictures/#?iff#? to df1:pictures QUIET

        With Workbench 2 and up, a new useful little symbol was added - the
'~' or tilda. (its obtained by shifting the key beneath the ESC key). The
tilda means 'not', so you can obtain a listing of all files that don't have
'iff' in their names with a command like this:

list ~ (#?iff#?)

        The brackets are optional, but they are there to try and make it
clearer to see what is going on. Things can start to get tricky, especially
when you use the '|' symbol, which have 'iff' or gif' in their names, use
the following:

list (#?iff#?|#?gif#?)

        If you want to miss out any files ending with 'info' (in other
words, the icons), use this:

list (#?gif|#?iff) (~#?info))

        You can see that although wildcards are powerful, they can quickly
get well out of hand. Sometimes you spend more time thinking of the
combination of #'s and ?'s and |'s to use than you would have copying each
file in turn. That's computing for you.

        Deleting old files is an essential chore that you need to do before
you fill your entire hard or floppy disk with rubbish. Wildcards can speed
things up:

delete #?.bak

        will remove any old files. It's worth testing the command by
swopping 'delete' with a 'list' before you accidentally nuke something
important. You especially don't want to enter.

delete #?

        Or you might loose everything... If you want to remove a directory
and the contents, use a command like this:

delete df0:pictures/#?

        Now this will delete the files in the pictures directory, but it
won't delete the directory itself. To do that include the ALL keyword, like
this:

delete df0:pictures/ ALL

        You might get an error message 'can't delete such-and-such is use'.
This could be because an ASSIGN has been made to the file, so check your
startup-sequence or User-startup for and references.


